description: Alteration (probably by influence of silo) of ensilage (1881), itself from French ensilage, from ensiler (“put in a silo”), from Spanish ensilar.

entries.meaning: Fermented green forage fodder stored in an airtight silo or clamp.
examples: Compared to the corn silages, the sweetclover silages are much higher in digestible crude protein, but lower in total digestible nutrients.

verbs.description: silage (third-person singular simple present silages, present participle silaging or silageing, simple past and past participle silaged)
